ECLOGUE VL—SILENUS.

ARGUMENr.-—Virgil begins by saying that his first efforts were in the style of Bucolic poetry. He then attempted Epic strains, but Apollo warned him not to forsake the shepherd's lays. Accordingly, he goes on (v. 13) to sing of Silenus, who was caught asleep, and obliged to obey the wishes of his captors.
